      "content": "The challenge of navigating a busy airport like Heathrow. It's a bit like trying to catch a quick nap in a crowded tavern, you never know when a rowdy group of travelers might disturb your slumber. In this case, the 90-minute layover might be a bit tight, but it's doable if you plan ahead and know the airport layout.\n\nTo make the most of your 90 minutes, consider the following: \n\n1. Check the airport's terminal layout and plan your route in advance. You can use the airport's website or a mapping app like Google Maps to get an idea of the distance between terminals.\n2. Research the security and immigration procedures for your specific flight. Some airports have separate security checkpoints for international flights, which can add to your overall travel time.\n3. Take advantage of the airport's fast-track security options, if available. This can help you speed through security and get to your gate more quickly.\n4. Consider the time of day and day of the week. If you're traveling during peak hours or on a busy day, you may need to factor in extra time for security and immigration.\n\nAs for the actual connection time, the recommended minimum is 45 minutes, but 60-90",
